        <section class="main-idea segment-opener" data-uuid="1135bd33ae5f44bab68fd5b94d953ae9">
            <article data-uuid="42bd49354e554aa689d568f4630a29f6">
                <h4 data-uuid="e8e68a2cdb1a4102bc3372dfbd147fc4">Main Idea</h4>
                <p class="main-idea" data-uuid="210b4fc520b4473fae80cbccf9778d83">The new government was based on popular sovereignty, balance of power, and federalism. </p>
                <h2 data-uuid="1e37bd5e814e412ba485829f9223e3cf">A New System of Government</h2>
                <div class="yellow-star-yellow-bar" data-uuid="c409898feebc46e9b9438d40f268ce28"></div>
            </article>
        </section>
        <p data-uuid="81507f4edfe24e90892612ecf779b2ac">On September 17, 1787, the delegates at the Constitutional Convention passed the Constitution. They had spent their summer debating key issues and creating a plan for a strong national government rooted in <dfn title="popular sovereignty">popular sovereignty</dfn>, the idea that political authority belongs to the people. Their plan included a scheme for limiting government power by dividing it among three different branches. In the end, all but three of the 42 delegates signed the Constitution. However, the Constitution, now in its final form, still needed to be approved by the states. </p>
        <h3 data-uuid="3c6bd2c2b87c4ccf9d52ec8586a6d6dc">Government Branches</h3>
        <p data-uuid="92ac7198dd9848ba92e35cff72874314">The framers of the Constitution divided the national government into three branches. The <dfn title="legislative branch">legislative branch</dfn> is responsible for proposing and passing laws. It is made up of the Senate and the House of Representatives. The <dfn title="executive branch">executive branch</dfn> includes the president and the departments that help run the government. The executive branch makes sure that laws are carried out. The <dfn title="judicial branch">judicial branch</dfn> is made up of all the national courts. This branch interprets laws, punishes criminals, and settles disputes between states.</p>
        <p data-uuid="2177dade38cf496a88da5bce68f4fae1"> The Constitution also includes a system of <dfn title="checks and balances">checks and balances</dfn>. Each branch has some checks, or controls, over the other branches. This system keeps any branch of the government from becoming too powerful. </p>
